# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: billy-meyer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:billy-meyer/1913-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1913 throughout the world.
[src:billy-meyer/1916-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1916 throughout the world.
[src:billy-meyer/1916-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:billy-meyer/1917-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1917 throughout the world.
[src:billy-meyer/1938-cleveland-indians-season] The **1938 Cleveland Indians season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:billy-meyer/1938-cleveland-indians-season] The team finished third in the American League with a record of 86–66, 13 games behind the New York Yankees.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-chicago-cubs-season] The **1940 Chicago Cubs season** was the 69th season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 65th in the National League and the 25th at Wrigley Field.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished fifth in the National League with a record of 75–79.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1940 Cincinnati Reds season** was the 58th season for the franchise.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati entered the season as the reigning National League champion, having been swept by the New York Yankees in the World Series the previous year.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] They would defeat the Detroit Tigers four games to three to take the World Series title.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati won 100 games for the first time in franchise history.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished first in the National League with a record of 100–53, winning the pennant by 12 games over the Brooklyn Dodgers, and the best record in MLB.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] They went on to face the Detroit Tigers in the 1940 World Series, beating them in seven games.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] This was their first championship since 1919.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] In August, back up catcher Willard Hershberger, depressed over what he felt was culpability for losing both games of a doubleheader, took his life.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] Coach Jimmie Wilson was added to the roster as the back up catcher.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The **1940 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1940 season.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The 37th edition of the World Series, it matched the Cincinnati Reds against the Detroit Tigers, with the Reds winning a closely contested seven-game series.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The victory secured the Reds the second championship in their franchise history and came 21 years after their victory over the scandal-tainted Chicago White Sox in 1919.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] This would be the Reds' last World Series championship for 35 years despite appearances in 1961, 1970, and 1972.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Meanwhile, Bill Klem worked the last of his record 18 World Series as an umpire.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Henry Quillen Buffkin Newsom, the father of Detroit's star pitcher Bobo Newsom, died in a Cincinnati hotel room the day after watching him win Game 1.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Newsom came back to hurl a shutout in Game 5 in his memory.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Called on to start a third time after a single day of rest by Tiger manager Del Baker, he pitched well in Game 7 until the seventh inning, when the Reds scored two runs to take the lead and eventually the game and the Series.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Reds' star pitchers Paul Derringer and Bucky Walters won two games apiece, with Derringer winning the decisive seventh game.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Walters hurled two complete games, allowing only eight hits and three runs combined.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] He also hit a home run in Game 6 in the midst of his 4–0 shutout, which sent the Series to a Game 7.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] It was redemption of sorts for the Reds, who returned to the World Series after being swept by the Yankees squad in 1939.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Reds' win in Game 2 against Detroit snapped a 10-game losing streak for the National League in the Series going back to Game 5 in 1937.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The victory culminated a somewhat turbulent season for the Reds, who played large stretches of the season without injured All-Star catcher Ernie Lombardi.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] And on August 3, Lombardi's backup, Willard Hershberger, committed suicide in Boston a day after a defensive lapse cost the Reds a game against the Bees.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Hershberger was hitting .309 at the time of his death.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Reds dedicated the rest of the season to "Hershie." One of the stars in the World Series was 40-year-old Jimmie Wilson.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Wilson had been one of the Reds' coaches before Hershberger's suicide forced him back onto the playing field as Lombardi's backup.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] With Lombardi hurting, Wilson did the bulk of the catching against Detroit and hit .353 for the Series and recorded the team's only stolen base.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Reds' manager Bill McKechnie became the first manager to win a World Series with two different teams, at the helm of the Pittsburgh Pirates in 1925, after trailing three games to one against Walter Johnson and the Washington Senators.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] This was the last time the Tigers lost in the World Series until 2006.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Bobo Newsom won Game 1 aided by a five-run second inning by Detroit.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Two singles and an error loaded the bases before Pinky Higgins drove in two runs with a single.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] A walk reloaded the bases before Dick Bartell's two-run single.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Bruce Campbell's RBI single knocked starter Paul Derringer out of the game.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Reds got on the board in the fourth when Ival Goodman hit a leadoff double and scored on Jimmy Ripple's single, but Campbell's two-run home run in the fifth off Whitey Moore extended the Tigers' lead to 7–1.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Reds got another run in the eighth when Billy Werber doubled and scored on Goodman's single, but nothing else as Detroit took a 1–0 series lead.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Tigers' win in Game 1 was the first World Series game won by a non-New York City team since 1935.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] In every World Series between 1935 and 1940, either both teams were from New York City or a New York City team won in a sweep (1938 and 1939).
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Next inning, Jimmy Ripple's two-run home run put the Reds up 4–2.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Back-to-back doubles by Walters and Billy Werber made it 5–2 Reds in the fourth.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Tigers got a run in the sixth on Hank Greenberg's RBI double after a walk and forceout in the sixth, but nothing else besides Pinky Higgins's leadoff double in the fifth as the Reds tied the series with a 5–3 win heading to Detroit.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Reds struck first in Game 3 when Billy Werber doubled to lead off the first off Tommy Bridges and scored on Ival Goodman's single, but the Tigers tied it in the fourth on Hank Greenberg's double-play after back-to-back leadoff singles off Jim Turner.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Detroit went up 5–1 in the seventh on two-run home runs by Rudy York and Pinky Higgins.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Reds got a run in the eighth on Mike McCormick's RBI single with two on, but in the bottom half, Greenberg hit a leadoff triple off Joe Beggs before Bruce Campbell's RBI single and Higgins's RBI double made it 7–2 Tigers.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] In the ninth after a leadoff single and error, RBI singles by Eddie Joost and Werber made it 7–4 Tigers, but Bridges struck out McCormick to end the game as Detroit took a 2–1 series lead.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] In Game 4, after a leadoff walk off Dizzy Trout, Ival Goodman's RBI double and Pinky Higgins's error on Jimmy Ripple's ground ball made it 2–0 Reds in the first.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] They made it 3–0 in the third on Jimmy Ripple's RBI double after two leadoff singles.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Tigers got on the board in the bottom half when Paul Derringer walked Barney McCosky, who moved to second on a groundout and scored on Hank Greenberg's RBI double, but the Reds got back that run in the fourth on Ival Goodman's sacrifice fly off Clay Smith after a leadoff walk and double.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Tigers got another run in the sixth Bruce Campbell singled with two outs and scored on Higgins's triple, but the Reds again got the run back in the eighth when Billy Werber singled with two outs off Archie McKain, moved to second on a wild pitch and scored on Mike McCormick's RBI single.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Derringer pitched a complete game to give the Reds a 5–2 win, tying the series 2–2.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Bobo Newsom allowed only three singles and two walks in the shutout, the day after his father died.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Detroit got on the board on Hank Greenberg's three-run home run after two leadoff singles in the third.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Next inning, Billy Sullivan drew a leadoff walk, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt and scored on Dick Bartell's double.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Two walks by starter Junior Thompson and reliever Whitey Moore loaded the bases before Hank Greenberg's sacrifice fly and after another walk, Bruce Campbell's two-run single made it 7–0 Tigers.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] They got another run in the eighth on Johnny Hutchings's wild pitch with two on and were just one win way from the championship heading back to Cincinnati.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Bucky Walters drew the Reds even with a five-hit shutout.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] He helped his own cause with an RBI fielder's choice in the sixth with the bases loaded off Johnny Gorsica and a solo home run in the eighth off Fred Hutchinson.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Schoolboy Rowe was knocked out after just 1⁄3 of an inning, allowing four hits, including RBI singles to Ival Goodman and Jimmy Ripple.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Reds' 4–0 win forced a final Game 7.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Detroit and pitcher Bobo Newsom clung to a 1-0 lead, courtesy of Charlie Gehringer's third inning RBI single off Paul Derringer, until the seventh.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Jimmy Ripple came up and then hit a double to score McCormick and tie the game.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Jimmie Wilson came up and delivered a perfect sacrifice bunt to advance Ripple to third base.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Ernie Lombardi, placed in the game to pinch-hit for Eddie Joost, was then intentionally walked to bring up Billy Myers.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] He hit a sacrifice fly on a ball to deep center that scored Ripple to deliver the go-ahead run.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] While Charlie Gehringer had a leadoff single in the 8th inning, the Tigers would not record a single hit afterwards, with Earl Averill grounding out to clinch the game and Series for the Reds.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] Bucky Walters, converted to pitching only after a torn cartilage (not repairable in those days) had slowed him down as a runner, was the fourth National League pitcher to hit a home run during a World Series game.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] This was the last title won by the Reds until 1975, where they defeated the Boston Red Sox in seven games after being seven outs away from elimination in Game 7.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] In between 1940 and 1975, the Reds lost in their next three appearances in the Fall Classic, in 1961, 1970, and 1972.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Tigers would return to the Fall Classic five years later, and defeated the Chicago Cubs in seven games.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] The Tigers would then win the World Series again in their next two appearances in 1968 and 1984.
[src:billy-meyer/1940-world-series] As of 2025, this is the only time that the Reds have ever clinched a World Series championship at home.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] A catcher who spent most of his 19-year active (1910–1928) playing career in the minor leagues, he threw and batted right-handed, and was listed as 5 feet 9 inches (1.75 m) tall and 170 pounds (77 kg).
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer broke into the majors with the 1913 Chicago White Sox, though he appeared in only one game.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Three years later, when he returned to the American League with the Philadelphia Athletics in 1916, he appeared in 50 games for a squad which won only 36 games and lost 117.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] The following year, he played in 62 games for an improved A's club which, however, still posted a 55–98 mark.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Then, a generation-and-a-half later, Meyer managed the 1952 Pittsburgh Pirates to the third-worst record in modern National League history, the Bucs winning only 42 of 154 games.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] However, during the period from 1932 through 1947, Meyer was a highly successful minor league manager, helming high-level teams in the New York Yankees' organization and winning four playoff championships.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] In addition, in 1948, Meyer's first season at the helm of the Pirates, he was selected *The Sporting News* Major League Manager of the Year, after he led the Bucs to a surprising first-division finish.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer was born in Knoxville, Tennessee, to William and Carrie Meyer.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] His father, born in the Grand Duchy of Baden in Germany, had emigrated to the United States at age 16 and operated a brewery in Knoxville.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer started playing baseball in grade school when his father bought him a catcher's mitt to catch his older brother.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] He was a good student until high school, when baseball became such a primary focus that it even resulted in a school suspension.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] His father also owned a brewery in Smithton, Pennsylvania, for a time and the younger Meyer worked there during vacation.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] During his sophomore year of high school, Meyer was offered $75 per month to catch for a Lakeland, Florida, team, but was expected to inherit the brewery so his father resisted the idea.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] He went regardless, and played so well a Sanford, Florida, team offered him $175 per month to play for them.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] He caught for other Florida teams and finally hit a championship-winning home run for Gainesville, Florida.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] When he returned to Tennessee with $250, his father never protested against baseball again.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] In 1915, Meyer played so well for a Davenport, Iowa, team Connie Mack acquired him to back up catcher Wally Schang for his major league Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] He recalled Mack had him catch for unpredictable young pitchers in order to save Schang.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] He played 50 games for the A's that year—and was thus on hand for a season in which the A's finished with the worst winning percentage in Major League Baseball history.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] As it turned out, this would be Meyer's last season in the majors as an active player.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] He collected 71 hits, with seven doubles, three triples and one home run, batted .236, and was credited with 21 runs batted in.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] After the season, Meyer was sold to the Louisville Colonels in the American Association.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] He would stay in Louisville for 11 years, and was a major contributor to the Colonels' American Association pennants in 1921 and 1925 under Joe McCarthy.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] When McCarthy was called up to manage the Chicago Cubs for the 1926 season, Meyer was named to succeed him at the helm of the Colonels.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] In his first season, Louisville won a second consecutive pennant with a team which included future Baseball Hall of Fame second baseman Billy Herman (whom Meyer would replace as skipper of the Pirates over 20 years later).
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] But when the Colonels promptly slumped to consecutive 100-loss seasons in 1927 and 1928, he was fired.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] At the same time, he was released as a player.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] After spending three years (1929–1931) as a coach with the Minneapolis Millers, an American Association rival of the Colonels, Meyer became manager of the 1932 Springfield Rifles of the Eastern League, an affiliate of the New York Yankees, where McCarthy was in his second season as manager.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer had the Rifles in first place on July 17 when the league folded due to Depression-related financial troubles.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Only two days later, was hired by the Binghamton Triplets of the New York–Pennsylvania League, another Yankees farm team.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer stayed in Binghamton for 31⁄2 years, winning the pennant in 1933 and split-season pennants in 1934 and 1935, and impressing George Weiss, head of the parent club's growing farm system.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] In 1936, Meyer moved up to the top-level Oakland Oaks of the Pacific Coast League, who then had a working agreement with the Bronx Bombers.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] He produced one playoff team in two seasons while at Oakland and was named to manage another top-level Yankees farm outlet, the Kansas City Blues of the American Association, in 1938.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] For the next ten years, Meyer alternated as the manager of the Blues (1938–1941; 1946–1947) and another elite Yankee farm club, the Newark Bears of the International League (1942–1945).
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] During that time, he won four pennants and finished second four times.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] His 1939 Blues, who finished 107–47 and won the Junior World Series for the second year in a row, were named the 12th best team in history by Minor League Baseball.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer was named Minor League Manager of the Year by *The Sporting News.* Overall, as a manager in the minors, Meyer won eight pennants, narrowly missed a ninth, and finished in the second division only twice.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] On July 6, 1944, Meyer and Newark were in last place, 30 games behind Bucky Harris and his Buffalo Bisons, and had lost to Buffalo seven consecutive times.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Newark rebounded by winning 30 of 34 games while Buffalo dropped into the second division, and missed winning the pennant by a fraction of a percent.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] In 19 seasons as a minor league skipper, Meyer's clubs won 1,605 and lost 1,325 (.548).
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] With Newark, one of his players, Nick Rhabe, threatened the general manager, "If you don't get me more dough, you'll be sorry." Rhabe carried through on the threat by running the bases poorly in a game.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer responded by knocking Rhabe down the dugout steps and kicking him off the team.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] In general, he was a disciplinarian who rarely screamed at players, similar to the style of Joe McCarthy.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer was an avid singer and a fan of George M.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] While in New York, Joe McCarthy introduced Meyer to Cohan.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer impressed him by singing songs that Cohan himself had not remembered writing.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] During his minor league managerial career, Meyer was considered for major league jobs several times.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] He was a candidate to be manager for the 1938 Cleveland Indians, but lost out to Ossie Vitt, his peer as the skipper of the Yanks' Newark Bears affiliate.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Later, he was derailed by the clubs' preference of the time for player–managers, thus saving salary during the Great Depression, or men whose major league résumés were stronger than Meyer's.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] When the Cubs fired Gabby Hartnett after the 1940 campaign Meyer was considered, but Jimmie Wilson got the job after helping the Cincinnati Reds win the 1940 World Series.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Louis Cardinals; Southworth would be elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame as a manager in 2008.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] The parent Yankees, meanwhile, had only one skipper from 1931 through 1945: McCarthy, who won eight American League pennants, seven World Series titles, and 1,438 regular-season games (an average of 96 a season) during that span.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] The hot-tempered, hard-drinking MacPhail also had a reputation for clashing with his managers.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer declined MacPhail's offer and instead returned to Kansas City, leading the 1947 Blues to a first-place finish, while the Yankees rebounded to win the 1947 pennant under Bucky Harris.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] The years 1946 and 1947 were also consequential for the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Frank McKinney—who had contacted Meyer about interviewing with the Braves after the 1945 season—became the Pirates' majority owner in August 1946.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] His ownership group, which included entertainer Bing Crosby and real-estate magnate John W.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Galbreath, hired a new management team at the close of the 1946 season.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] As general manager, they selected former Yankees farm system official Roy Hamey.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Then they acquired Billy Herman from the Braves and named the future Baseball Hall of Fame second baseman their player–manager for 1947.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] However the managerial move backfired: the 37-year-old Herman was at the end of the line as a player, appearing in only 18 games and hitting .213, and his Pirates stumbled to the club's second consecutive seventh-place season in the eight-team National League.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Herman resigned with one game left in the 1947 campaign.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Hamey, who had worked with Meyer at both Binghamton and Kansas City in the Yankee organization, and McKinney then turned to Meyer, who accepted their offer to become Pittsburgh's pilot for 1948.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer received an important endorsement from Joe McCarthy, who had followed Meyer's work closely with future Yankees stars in Oakland, Kansas City and Newark.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] McCarthy was impressed enough to say Meyer had been the best manager in the minor leagues at the time, and predicted that he would be one of the best in the majors as well.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] In 1948, in his first season, Pittsburgh rose from seventh place to fourth in the standings—and just 81⁄2 games out of first.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] The 21-game improvement to 83–71 earned Meyer *The Sporting News* Major League Manager of the Year.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] The Pirates also led the National League in attendance.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Despite the home run heroics of Ralph Kiner, the Pirates dropped to sixth place in 1949.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Reportedly, Meyer lost the team when he suggested to reporters a player had run into a pitchout on his own when he had actually given the player a hit and run sign.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] In December 1950, the Pirate ownership replaced Hamey with Branch Rickey, whose solution was to purge the team of high-salaried veterans and bring up young players from the farm system—the same tactic he'd used to rebuild the St.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] However, it backfired disastrously in Pittsburgh, and Meyer was saddled with what amounted to a minor-league team at the major-league level.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] The Pirates managed to improve to seventh in 1951, but lost 112 games in 1952—the second-worst record in franchise history, and the third-worst in modern (post-1900) National League history.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer resigned at the end of that campaign.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] In 1954, the Pirates retired Meyer's uniform number #1.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] It was only the seventh number retired by a team in AL/NL history, with Meyer the first person who was primarily a manager to have his number retired.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Several later historians have remarked on the puzzling circumstances of the number retirement, given that Meyer had a managing record of 317–452 (.412) over only five seasons in Pittsburgh and never finishing higher than fourth in the league.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer also was honored by his native city of Knoxville, where he maintained his home and had married a classmate from grade school, Madelon Warters, in 1932.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] The city's baseball park, for years the home of the minor-league Knoxville Smokies, was named Bill Meyer Stadium in his honor.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] The stadium was closed in 1999 and demolished in 2003.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer appears in the Norman Rockwell painting *Tough Call*.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] After his managing days, Meyer worked as a scout and troubleshooter for the Pirates until he suffered a stroke in 1955.
[src:billy-meyer/billy-meyer] Meyer died two years later, in Knoxville, of heart and kidney ailments at age 64.
